Linear mixed-effects models in R

There are two widely used packages to estimate linear mixed-effects models in R: nlme and lme4. The nlme package is older and can estimate linear and non-linear mixed-effects models with Normally distributed errors. It allows you to specify various specialized covariance structures for the random-effects and also allows you to model correlations between the errors. The lme4 package is newer (and developed by Douglas Bates, an authority on mixed-effects models who also co-developed the nlme package), simpler to use, allows you to specify mixed-effects models with non-Gaussian errors (e.g., mixed effects logistic regression models), is faster, and works better for models with many random effects. Here, we’ll use lme4.

The way you specify a mixed-effects model in lme4 is very similar to the way you specify a general linear model. For models with Normally distributed errors, you make use of the lmer function (for Linear Mixed-Effects Regression). The (important) bits of the syntax are

lmer(formula, data = NULL, REML = TRUE,...)

where

  • formula is a model formula, just like for the lm function, with an additional option to specify random effects. You can specify that you want to include a random part of an effect by enclosing a predictor (or 1 for the intercept) by parentheses. You also need to specify the unit of observation on which the random parts depends, by a “|” sign and then specifying the variable which contains the levels of the units of observation. So, for instance, if you have a model with dependent variable y, a single predictor called week, and there is a variable called id which contains the ID number of each participant, and you want to include a random intercept dependent on id, you could specify the formula as y ~ 1 + week + (1|id). If you also want to include a random slope for week, you could specify the formula as y ~ 1 + week + (1 + week|id). By enclosing multiple effects within the same parentheses, you are allowing these effects to be correlated. If you want the random effects to be independent, you should specify them in separate parentheses, so y ~ 1 + week + (1|id) + (0 + week|id). Note that it is necessary to put the 0 with week in this case to explicitly state that this bit should not include an intercept (just like lm, lmer assumes intercepts by default).
  • data should be a data frame in the “long” format (e.g., unlike for repeated-measures, you should have multiple rows for each participant, one row for each repeated-measure)
  • REML is a logical argument specifying whether to use Restricted Maximum Likelihood (REML = TRUE) or Maximum Likelihood (REML = FALSE)

For example, let’s use the Reisby.sav data discussed in the lecture. Let’s estimate a mixed-effects model with level 1 structure: \[\text{HamD}_{hi} = \beta_{0i} + \beta_{1i} \text{week}_{hi} + \epsilon_{hi}\] and level 2 structure \[\begin{align*} \beta_{0i} &= \beta_0 + \alpha_{0i} \\ \beta_{1i} &= \beta_1 + \alpha_{1i} \end{align*}\] i.e. a model with both random intercepts and random slopes, and let’s allow a correlation between the random effects.

# load the data
library(foreign)
dat <- as.data.frame(read.spss("Reisby.sav"))
head(dat)
##    Id HamD Week WeekSq Endogenous EndoWeek EndoWeekSq
## 1 101   26    0      0         -1        0          0
## 2 101   22    1      1         -1       -1         -1
## 3 101   18    2      4         -1       -2         -4
## 4 101    7    3      9         -1       -3         -9
## 5 101    4    4     16         -1       -4        -16
## 6 101    3    5     25         -1       -5        -25
# load the lme4 package
library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'lme4'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     sigma
## estimate a mixed-effects model with REML (default)
mod <- lmer(HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1 + Week|Id),data=dat)
# summarize the results
summary(mod)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']

##    Data: dat

Note that the output provides you with the parameter estimates, but no \(p\)-values. This is because the author (for good reasons, actually) doesn’t believe in the method of correcting the degrees of freedom of the test statistics to obtain valid test results. Also note that SPSS provides further additional output, such as Wald tests for the random effects variances, and overall model results such as the “-2 log likelihood”.

Multilevel models

To specify a multilevel model, you can indicate the hierarchical structure in the random effects part of the formula, by separating levels in the hierarchy by a “/” sign. For instance, if you want to estimate a model in which you want a random intercept for classrooms, and students within classrooms, you can specify the random effects part as

(1 | classrooms/students)

which you can read as “students nested within classrooms”. If you want to estimate a model in which you want a random intercept for schools, classrooms within schools, and students within classrooms, you can specify the random effects part as

(1 | schools/classrooms/students)

Obtaining the -2 log likelihood and likelihood ratio tests

To get the “-2 log likelihood” value, you can use the logLik function:

# the log likelihood
logLik(mod)
## 'log Lik.' -1109.959 (df=6)
# multiply this by -2 to get the -2 log likelihood:
-2 * logLik(mod)
## 'log Lik.' 2219.918 (df=6)
# get the AIC
AIC(mod)
## [1] 2231.918

Note that these are computed for a model which was estimated by REML, so these are technically “log restricted likelihood” values. You should really re-estimate the model with ML to get the correct log likelihood values:

modML <- lmer(HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1 + Week|Id),data=dat,REML=FALSE)
## you can also do this with the refitML function:
modML <- refitML(mod)
logLik(modML)
## 'log Lik.' -1109.519 (df=6)
-2 * logLik(modML)
## 'log Lik.' 2219.038 (df=6)

To get a likelihood-ratio test, you can use the anova function. Let’s test whether the covariance between intercept and slope is significant by estimating a model where we assume the random effects are independent, and then comparing this to the model we estimated above:

modMLindep <- lmer(HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1|Id) + (0 + Week|Id),data=dat,REML=FALSE)
anova(modMLindep,modML)
## Data: dat
## Models:
## modMLindep: HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1 | Id) + (0 + Week | Id)
## modML: HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1 + Week | Id)
##            Df    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## modMLindep  5 2231.4 2251.0 -1110.7   2221.4                         
## modML       6 2231.0 2254.6 -1109.5   2219.0 2.3364      1     0.1264

Obtaining confidence intervals for the random-effects covariances

Unfortunately, there is no easy way to get Wald tests for the random-effects covariances to replicate the SPSS output. But perhaps that is really a blessing, as the Wald test is pretty rubbish anyway (as explained in the lecture). The lme4 package does allow you a better way to infer whether a (co-)variance is significantly different from 0 by computing confidence intervals around the parameters. These can be obtained via the confint function, which provides a confidence interval for each parameter in the model.

confint(mod)
## Computing profile confidence intervals ...
##                  2.5 %      97.5 %
## .sig01       2.6370456  4.62552904
## .sig02      -0.5493499  0.08827253
## .sig03       1.1191403  1.83470431
## .sigma       3.2035517  3.83414862
## (Intercept) 22.4915808 24.66269398
## Week        -2.7924190 -1.96194440

Note that the names for the random effects (co-)variances aren’t very clear, unfortunately, being labelled as “.sig01”, “.sig02”, etc. If you think about these as being in a covariance matrix, then they are reported in the order of the upper-diagonal, reading row-wise, so first the variance of the first random effect, then the covariance between random effect 1 and 2, then covariance between random-effect 1 and 3, …, variance of second random effect, covariance between random effect 2 and 3, then covariance between random-effect 2 and 4, …, etc. The confidence interval for “.sigma” is the confidence interval for the error variance.

Plotting model predictions

To get plots of the model predictions for each unit of observation (e.g., participants), we can first save the model predictions in the data.frame, using the predict function called on a model fitted by lmer. Note that this function only gives predictions for those cases where the dependent variable is not missing (as missing values are excluded when estimating the models).

# save the model predictions in a variable called "pred"
# only assign predictions to those rows where HamD is *not* missing:
dat$pred[!is.na(dat$HamD)] <- predict(mod)
## load the ggplot2 package for pretty plots
library(ggplot2)
# create a plot' the ggplot2 package is not easy to use
# but you can use this template to create similar plots
# just replace the y, x, group, colour arguments for 
# other data frames (as well as the 'pred' name if you
# call this something else)
# the geom_point draws the dots of the observed data
# the geom_line draws the lines for the model predictions
ggplot(dat,aes(y=HamD,x=Week,group=factor(Id),colour=factor(Id))) + geom_point() + geom_line(aes(y=pred,x=Week,group=factor(Id),colour=factor(Id)))
## Warning: Removed 21 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 13 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

## you can also make separate plots for each level of endogeneous
ggplot(dat,aes(y=HamD,x=Week,group=factor(Id),colour=factor(Id))) + geom_point() + geom_line(aes(y=pred,x=Week,group=factor(Id),colour=factor(Id))) + facet_wrap(~Endogenous)
## Warning: Removed 21 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

## Warning: Removed 13 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

Obtaining p-values with the lmerTest package

To get \(p\)-values for the fixed-effects, just like SPSS provides, you can use the lmerTest package, which corrects the degrees of freedom with the Satterthwaite correction. When you load the lmerTest package, it defines an extended lmer function which allows you to compute the \(p\)-values. After loading the lmerTest package, when you call the summary function on an estimated model, the output will show the \(p\)-values:

library(lmerTest)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lmerTest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:lme4':
## 
##     lmer
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     step
mod <- lmer(HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1 + Week|Id),data=dat)
summary(mod)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML t-tests use Satterthwaite approximations
##   to degrees of freedom [lmerMod]
## Formula: HamD ~ 1 + Week + (1 + Week | Id)
##    Data: dat
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 2219.9
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.7358 -0.4982  0.0332  0.5145  3.6793 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev. Corr 
##  Id       (Intercept) 12.944   3.598         
##           Week         2.126   1.458    -0.28
##  Residual             12.213   3.495         
## Number of obs: 375, groups:  Id, 66

If you want the omnibus tests for factors, you can use the anova function on the model:

anova(mod)
